message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. Male internal and external reproductive structures are developed from the Wolffian ducts, which are stimulated by the presence of testosterone produced by Leydig cells, and inhibited by Mullerian inhibiting substance (MIS) produced by Sertoli cells. The lack of a uterus suggests that the MIS produced by Sertoli cells has caused the regression of Mullerian ducts, which would have developed into a uterus if not inhibited. Thus, the correct answer is Sertoli cells.

The lack of a uterus in a newborn male can be attributed to the actions of Sertoli cells, which support the development of the testes and male reproductive structures. Theca cells and Granulosa cells are involved in female reproductive development, and Reticularis cells are involved in adrenal gland function, not reproductive development.

The lack of a uterus is due to the absence of Mullerian inhibiting factor (MIF), which is produced by Sertoli cells in males and causes the regression of the Mullerian ducts that would otherwise develop into the uterus and fallopian tubes in females. Theca and granulosa cells are involved in ovarian function, while reticularis cells produce androgens in the adrenal gland.

Sertoli cells secrete anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH), which leads to the regression of Müllerian ducts, preventing the development of the uterus and fallopian tubes. Theca cells and granulosa cells are associated with ovarian follicle development, while reticularis cells are part of the adrenal gland.
